<h1>LG Dryer Won't Start or Turn On — Causes and How We Fix It</h1>

<p>When your LG dryer won't start, the first thing we need to know is whether it has power at all or whether it powers on but refuses to run a cycle. These are two completely different problems with different causes. A completely dead dryer — blank display, no lights, clicking sounds when you press any button but no response — points to a power supply issue. A dryer that displays normally but won't start a cycle points to a safety interlock, a failed start switch, or a mechanical problem the dryer detected. We carry common parts like thermal fuses and door latches on every truck across Los Angeles County, Orange County, and Ventura County, and we resolve most not-starting calls on the first visit.</p>

<h2>Before You Call Us — Quick Checks</h2>
<p>Three things to try before scheduling a visit that might save you the service call entirely:</p>
<p><strong>Child lock:</strong> LG dryers have a child lock that disables all controls. If the display shows a lock icon or "CL," hold the designated buttons for 3 seconds to deactivate. We get these calls weekly in Pasadena and Irvine — always a free fix.</p>
<p><strong>Circuit breaker:</strong> Electric dryers run on a 240V double-pole breaker. If one leg trips, the dryer may display normally but won't run. Reset the breaker fully — push to OFF first, then back to ON. Intermittent starting in older homes in Pasadena and Glendale with aging electrical systems is often traced back here.</p>
<p><strong>Error codes:</strong> Check the display for any error code before calling. Note the exact code — d80, dE, tE1, whatever shows — and tell us when you call. It tells us exactly what to address.</p>

<h2>Scenario 1 — No Power At All (Blank Display, Clicking, No Response)</h2>

<div class="diag-card">
  <div class="diag-title">
    Thermal Fuse Blown
    <span class="sev-badge sev-high">Most common cause of complete shutdown</span>
  </div>
  <div class="diag-tags">
    <div class="diag-tag">Dryer completely dead</div>
    <div class="diag-tag">No display, no response</div>
    <div class="diag-tag">Usually caused by clogged vent</div>
  </div>
  <p>On many LG models the thermal fuse is wired into the main power circuit — when it blows, the entire dryer goes dead, not just the heating circuit. You press the power button and nothing happens — not even clicking. The thermal fuse blows when the dryer overheats, almost always because the exhaust vent is clogged. We test it first on every no-power call because it's the most common complete-shutdown cause. We also clear and test vent airflow as part of the job — a new fuse in a clogged system blows again within weeks. We also check terminal block connections at the back of the dryer while we're in there — loose connections from vibration over years of use can cause the same dead-dryer symptom. Cost: $280–350. See <a href="/repairs/lg-dryer-thermal-fuse-replacement/">thermal fuse replacement</a>.</p>
</div>

<div class="diag-card">
  <div class="diag-title">
    Power Supply or Control Board Failure
    <span class="sev-badge sev-mid">Less common — after thermal fuse ruled out</span>
  </div>
  <div class="diag-tags">
    <div class="diag-tag">Completely dead — thermal fuse tests good</div>
    <div class="diag-tag">Outlet and breaker confirmed good</div>
    <div class="diag-tag">More common after power surge</div>
  </div>
  <p>If the thermal fuse is intact, the outlet delivers correct voltage, and the breaker is fine, we look at the control board and internal power supply. Power surges — more common in older neighborhoods in Glendale and Long Beach with aging electrical infrastructure — can damage the control board in ways that leave the dryer completely unresponsive. We verify the electrical supply with a professional multimeter before recommending a board replacement. Control board: $320–420. We rule out everything cheaper first.</p>
</div>

<h2>Scenario 2 — Powers On But Won't Start</h2>

<div class="diag-card">
  <div class="diag-title">
    Door Switch Failed
    <span class="sev-badge sev-high">Most common — powers on won't run</span>
  </div>
  <div class="diag-tags">
    <div class="diag-tag">Display works normally</div>
    <div class="diag-tag">Press start — silence or clicking, no drum</div>
    <div class="diag-tag">No error code displayed</div>
  </div>
  <p>The door switch tells the dryer the door is closed and it's safe to operate. When it fails, the dryer powers on and the display works normally — but pressing start produces nothing, or just a clicking sound with no drum movement. No error code, just silence or clicking. The drum light inside is on a separate circuit so it may still work even when the door switch has failed. We test the switch with a multimeter — failed switch reads open when the door is closed. Cheap fix, fast repair. Cost: $150–200 including labor.</p>
</div>

<div class="diag-card">
  <div class="diag-title">
    Error Code Preventing Start
    <span class="sev-badge sev-mid">Common</span>
  </div>
  <div class="diag-tags">
    <div class="diag-tag">Code visible on display</div>
    <div class="diag-tag">d80/d90/d95 most common</div>
    <div class="diag-tag">Dryer won't run until issue resolved</div>
  </div>
  <p>LG dryers won't start a cycle when they detect a problem. The most common codes that prevent starting: d80, d90, d95 — airflow restriction. dE, dE1, dE2 — door error. tE1, tE2, tE3 — thermistor error. PS — power supply issue on some models. Note the exact code and tell us when you call — it tells us exactly what to address. See the full error code breakdown below.</p>
</div>

<div class="diag-card">
  <div class="diag-title">
    Broken Belt — Dryer Detects No Drum Rotation
    <span class="sev-badge sev-mid">Often missed diagnosis</span>
  </div>
  <div class="diag-tags">
    <div class="diag-tag">Starts briefly then stops</div>
    <div class="diag-tag">Motor hums momentarily</div>
    <div class="diag-tag">Drum spins freely by hand</div>
  </div>
  <p>Some LG models detect that the drum isn't rotating and shut down within seconds. If the belt has snapped, the drum won't turn when the motor engages — the dryer starts, senses no drum rotation, stops itself. Press start, hear a brief hum, then silence again. Open the door and spin the drum by hand — if it moves freely with no resistance, the belt is broken. Cost: $260–320. See <a href="/repairs/lg-dryer-belt-replacement/">belt replacement</a>.</p>
</div>

<div class="diag-card">
  <div class="diag-title">
    Start Button or Control Panel Failure
    <span class="sev-badge sev-low">Less common</span>
  </div>
  <div class="diag-tags">
    <div class="diag-tag">Other buttons respond, start doesn't</div>
    <div class="diag-tag">Works intermittently</div>
    <div class="diag-tag">Needs to be held longer each time</div>
  </div>
  <p>The start button itself can fail on heavily used machines. If other panel buttons respond normally but start specifically doesn't — or if it works intermittently, needing to be held progressively longer — the button or its control board connection is failing. We see this on older DLEX and DLGX models in Torrance and Santa Monica. Depending on the model this may involve replacing the entire control panel assembly.</p>
</div>

<h2>LG Dryer Error Codes That Prevent Starting</h2>
<p><strong>d80, d90, d95</strong> — Vent blockage (80%, 90%, 95%). Clear the vent and the dryer will start. Don't just reset — the blockage causes overheating that will blow the thermal fuse.</p>
<p><strong>dE, dE1, dE2</strong> — Door error. Check nothing is caught in the door seal. If door closes fully but code persists, the door switch is failing.</p>
<p><strong>tE1, tE2, tE3</strong> — Thermistor (temperature sensor) error. Sensor is reading incorrectly. Dryer won't run until addressed.</p>
<p><strong>PS</strong> — Power supply error. Usually indicates a voltage issue at the outlet or internal power supply problem.</p>
<p><strong>PF</strong> — Power failure. Dryer detected a power interruption. Usually clears by pressing start again. If it persists, there's an intermittent power issue.</p>
<p><strong>CL</strong> — Child lock active. Not a malfunction. Hold designated buttons 3 seconds to deactivate.</p>

