<h2>Questions We Get on These Calls</h2>

<h3>My LG dryer is completely dead — no display, no power. What's wrong?</h3>
<p>Check the circuit breaker first — reset it fully. If the breaker is fine, the most likely cause is a blown thermal fuse — a safety device that shuts the dryer down completely when it overheats. We test it in minutes on-site. Cost: $280–350 if that's the issue.</p>

<h3>My LG dryer turns on but won't start when I press the button. What's happening?</h3>
<p>Three things to check yourself first: child lock (look for lock icon or "CL" on display), error code on the display, and whether the door is fully latching. If all three are clear and the dryer still won't start — no sound, or just a clicking when you press start — the door switch has most likely failed. Cost: $150–200.</p>

<h3>My LG dryer shows d80 or d90 and won't start. What do I do?</h3>
<p>The vent is clogged and the dryer is refusing to run to prevent overheating. Don't just reset the code — clear the vent first. Call us and we'll clear the vent, test airflow, and confirm the dryer starts cleanly. If the thermal fuse also blew, we replace it at the same visit.</p>

<h3>My LG dryer starts for a second then stops. What's wrong?</h3>
<p>Spin the drum by hand with the machine unplugged. Spins freely with no resistance = broken belt. The dryer starts, detects no drum rotation, and shuts itself off as a safety measure. Belt replacement: $260–320.</p>

<h3>How long does it take to fix an LG dryer that won't start?</h3>
<p>Most not-starting repairs are done within 1–2 hours on the same visit. We carry thermal fuses and door latches on every truck — the two most common causes. Less common parts like control boards may require ordering.</p>

